<div id="review_3515646943" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3515646943" />
    <a title="Cormac Healy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/40842414-cormac-healy"><img alt="Cormac Healy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1553060656p2/40842414.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3515646943?book_show_action=true">Sep 10, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cormac Healy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cormac Healy" href="/user/show/40842414-cormac-healy">Cormac Healy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3515646943" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15081485668630306341">I think is probably about as good an overview of European exploitation of Africa over a 40-year stretch as it is possible to write. The characters are vivid, it provides agency and humanity to all the characters (even those who it is pretty impossible to understand), and keeps things moving in an entertaining fashion. <br/><br/>There were a couple of problems though, more I think with the scope and scale than with the writing itself. <br/><br/>Firstly, the topic is just too big. Over 40 years of history (and it is </span>
  <span id="freeText15081485668630306341" style="display:none">I think is probably about as good an overview of European exploitation of Africa over a 40-year stretch as it is possible to write. The characters are vivid, it provides agency and humanity to all the characters (even those who it is pretty impossible to understand), and keeps things moving in an entertaining fashion. <br /><br />There were a couple of problems though, more I think with the scope and scale than with the writing itself. <br /><br />Firstly, the topic is just too big. Over 40 years of history (and it is never made abundantly clear why the author chose these exact years, considering European influence in Africa certainly predated 1876) over a huge space of land, involving some of the most bizarre and memorable characters and events, is just too much for one book. The timeline at the back does help you keep track, but there are times when it is just too much. <br /><br />In particular, I found the chapters on the countries of the Sahara and the Sahel particularly hard to follow, probably more due to my own lack of knowledge, but it was just too much when I was also trying to keep track of what Kruger was up to in Transvaal, Stanley in the depths of the Congo, and Gordon in Sudan. I think a large part of this was the frequent French names of institutions and government organisations, which I just never could really get a hold of.<br /><br />It was also unusual not to cover Liberia in more detail. Considering that at the end of the Scramble only Ethiopia (which rightly gets 2 chapters to itself) and Liberia were independent of European influence, it would have been interesting to learn more about why Pakenham thought this was. Was the fear of American retribution if anyone messed with their pet project great enough to keep away the hands of Europe? It seems strange, considering how little compunction and logic was used in the rest of the Scramble. <br /><br />Overall, I enjoyed it a lot though, and gained a lot from it. I read another Pakenham book, just on the Boer War. I would definitely recommend reading this first, as the Boer War is essentially placed into just 2 chapters, and then if you fancy a seriously deep dive, then by all means crack on. <br /><br />4.5/5</span>
  <a data-text-id="15081485668630306341" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

