    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1826609000" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1826609000" />
    <a title="aditya" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/42505-aditya"><img alt="aditya" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1826609000?book_show_action=true">Nov 30, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="aditya" class="user" itemprop="url" name="aditya" href="/user/show/42505-aditya">aditya</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/42505-aditya?shelf=influential">influential</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1826609000" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9355540063174212251">This book offers a really solid overview of what happened between 1850ish and 1900 in Africa that led to the entire dark continent being colonized and ruthlessly and arbitrarily exploited by the four Great Powers (UK, France, Russia, Germany), and also by sidey powers such as the Ottomans and hustlers like King Leopold of Belgium, principally in 30-odd years, the period known to historians as &quot;The Scramble for Africa&quot;. <br/><br/>Before encountering this book, I really didn&apos;t grok that a big reason for the</span>
  <span id="freeText9355540063174212251" style="display:none">This book offers a really solid overview of what happened between 1850ish and 1900 in Africa that led to the entire dark continent being colonized and ruthlessly and arbitrarily exploited by the four Great Powers (UK, France, Russia, Germany), and also by sidey powers such as the Ottomans and hustlers like King Leopold of Belgium, principally in 30-odd years, the period known to historians as "The Scramble for Africa". <br /><br />Before encountering this book, I really didn't grok that a big reason for the exploration and colonization of Africa was the Liberal movement to end the slave trade at its root: Livingstone's 3Cs of Civilization, Commerce and Christianity to eliminate slavery. At the time he made his clarion call to explorers to open up Africa to the world in the 1860s and 1870s, slave raids were common across wide swathes of especially North and West Africa, and increasing as the trade proved lucrative and more and more ruthless Arabs and African tribes jumped on the bandwagon. <br /><br />I also realized that typically in African colonization situations the white settlers on the ground and their corporations and their promoters at home were much more greedy and racist than the higher-minded electorates and governments at home, and so all over Africans and other natives were often treated as or worse than cattle. Despite the difference in ideals, African rights are routinely betrayed in favor of any strategic priority or common European interest by all European parties all the time, it's really about the level of handwringing that precedes or follows. <br /><br />The whole reel of situations precipitated during the scramble is a giant mess. It's so messy that by the end the prose starts seeming a little purple, especially when Pakenham repeats colorful imagery used before to describe tense situations. But it's the truth that is just bananas. So much went on that for the scramble to start sounding like the battles in LOTR was to a certain extent inevitable.<br /><br />Another remarkable takeaway was that Africa in this period was all conquered on foot and then later on huge railways are cut, typically through slave or indentured labor. That's why waterways like the Nile, Niger and Congo rivers are the obsession of different governments and explorers. <br /><br />Another astounding realization is that there'd be no economy in commodities in Africa without the huge capital expense, or the discount of the slave labor. Probably much of the indentured labor in many parts is still entrenched.<br /><br />Actually a 4 star book because Pakenham's own biases do show here and there. His predictions for Africa's future turn out to be horribly dated in a way that exposes his viewpoint, he's clearly overly fond of the British Empire and its trappings. But despite that understandable Anglophile bias his book is so incredibly influential to me and such a grand effort of research I handily give it a 5 on 5 rating. This book will influence my thinking forever. What a trip.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9355540063174212251" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

