    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1692597446" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1692597446" />
    <a title="Nigel Kotani" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/53367524-nigel-kotani"><img alt="Nigel Kotani" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1457103765p2/53367524.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1692597446?book_show_action=true">Jul 09, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nigel Kotani" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nigel Kotani" href="/user/show/53367524-nigel-kotani">Nigel Kotani</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1692597446" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16857716529891031465">Torn between 4 stars and 5, and would like to have given it 4.5, but ultimately the minor issues I had with this book were of my own making, so 5 it is.<br/><br/>First of all, if you like well-written non-fiction, particularly in the history genre (which, as I get older, I do more and more) then this book is up there with any I&apos;ve ever read. Sweeping, epic, magnificent etc etc. It covers the colonial history of Africa from Livingstone to the handing over of Congo from Leopold to the Belgian State (with a </span>
  <span id="freeText16857716529891031465" style="display:none">Torn between 4 stars and 5, and would like to have given it 4.5, but ultimately the minor issues I had with this book were of my own making, so 5 it is.<br /><br />First of all, if you like well-written non-fiction, particularly in the history genre (which, as I get older, I do more and more) then this book is up there with any I've ever read. Sweeping, epic, magnificent etc etc. It covers the colonial history of Africa from Livingstone to the handing over of Congo from Leopold to the Belgian State (with a bemusing epilogue written before the end of apartheid and when Mugabe was still regarded as an exemplary statesman).<br /><br />The strength of this book is that it examines the stories right from their geopolitical and diplomatic perspective, through the politics of the individual imperialist countries as their internal disputes affected their foreign policy, through the military aspects of individual campaigns, and down to the "boys' own adventure" level of people hacking through jungles. (Hence the "sweeping, epic, magnificent....").<br /><br />My problem with the book is that its scale and scope are so enormous that each individual chapter effectively constitutes an essay in its own right and has to be read at a single sitting if the reader is not to lose the plot. Several times in the first half of the book I suddenly found myself thinking "what on earth is going on", and wading through to the end of the chapter without getting much benefit from it. <br /><br />Once I had figured out that I shouldn't pick it up unless I could finish a chapter I enjoyed it a lot more, and at the chapter level it is a real page-turner. The problem was that, with each chapter taking about 45 minutes to read, and with it containing nearly 40 chapters (the book is over 750 pages), that approach meant that it took me a couple of months to read. I'd therefore recommend reading it when you have the time and space for that kind of epic (e.g. on holiday, although it's not obvious holiday reading material), but recommend it I do. Wholeheartedly. It's bloody brilliant.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16857716529891031465" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


